Handle is antler and the sheath is brass. This was brought back from Europe after WWII by my great uncle Melton Bowman from Bend Oregon died in Bends Jail for a drunk fight he got arrested for but they left the window open in his cell over night during winter and he died from drunk hypothermia in police custody in 1968. He was Army, his unit forgotten but according to him he did serve as a special envoy with the British SAS during WWII on pre Normandy invasion mission. According to him, this dagger was from his first German Officer that he killed on that mission. He carried it the rest off the war on him, so some dings and wear are noticeable, but still in good shape. Take into consideration THIS DAGGER IS EXTREMELY RARE!!! The only other one I could find with the same grip was for sale in England and he wanted over a thousand pounds! About $2000. I'm asking $500. No trades, cash only thanks! Own a piece of history, the price will only go up with time!
